518. Hic ille est. Cf. v. 787, Most. 162. sperabilest. In the old spelling -253 est became -est, not -z'st. Nonius (224 Μ.) seems to attest similest (MSS. simile cst> for similis est in the early dramatists, with examples from Titinius, Naevius and Novius, and again (p. 198 M.) qualest (MSS. euleu> for qualis est in Plaut. Amph. 537 (where the original of our MSS. of Plautus apparently had quale est, but qualest in the following line), and (p. 218) Ρῑῗηφιθεί (MSS. pz'ozyue est) for pinquis est in a line of Novius, and possibly (p. 227 Μ.) talest for talis est in a line of Titinius: uirqo nulla talest Setiae (MSS. est talis etiae). We have many indications of this spelling in our MSS. of Plautus. (For a list of them see Leo Plaut. Forseliuugyeou p. 259). But the evidence at our disposal seems to confine this spelling to -z's when in conjunction with est (or es) and does not entitle us to accept Leo’s explanation of fidele sis in v. 439 as a by—form of fidelis sis.
